Bike-demand forecasting model.

Approach: ride-level logs are aggregated into station-hour demand, reconstructing
the zero-demand daytime hours (06:00-22:00) inside each station's active window so
the training distribution matches the evaluator's. Features combine cyclical time
encodings (hour/weekday sin-cos), weather, calendar flags, and OSM station metadata,
plus hierarchical mean-demand target encodings with graceful fallback
(station x hour-of-week -> station -> city x hour-of-week -> city -> global). This
fallback chain is what lets the model generalize to sparse/unseen stations and
cities. Two LightGBM regressors are trained (objective="poisson" and
objective="regression_l1") and averaged; predictions are clipped to be non-negative.

Reproduce:
    cd submissions/challenge_1_IDs
    python train.py        # reads ../../dataset/train_set.csv, writes weights.joblib

Rename this folder to challenge_1_<ID1>_<ID2> before submitting, and fill in the
team names (line 1) and IDs (line 2) above.
